 the 1620s; <i>c.</i> 1650 he moved to Duxbury and subesequently to Bridgewater. He had many prominent descendants, among them one of the earliest families on Martha's Vineyard. — The surname <i>Bassett</i> of French origin (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Armand, Adrien, Normand, Alphonse, Lucien, Cecile, Herve, Jacques, Laurent, Aime.","French: topographic name designating a small wood of birches, from Occitan <i>bès</i> ‘birch tree’ (see   Besse  ), or a habitational name from (La) Bessette, the name of several places in the southern part of France.","Alternatively, an altered form of French <b>Besset</b>: topographic name, a cognate of 1 above. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Bassett was born in 1070, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Agatha de Brus. He died in 1167, in his hometown, at the age of 97."},"et":{"1070–1167":"1070–1167","1072–1154":"1072–1154","1090–1165":"1090–1165","1090":"1090","1167":"1167","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1072":"1072","1070":"1070","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wallingford, Oxfordshire, England":"Wallingford, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Headington, Oxfordshire, E